1. Input/Output (I/O)

a.pinMode(pin, mode): Tells the Arduino if a pin is a "mouth" (OUTPUT) or an "ear" (INPUT).
b.digitalWrite(pin, value): Sends a simple ON (HIGH/5V) or OFF (LOW/0V) signal.
c.digitalRead(pin): Listens for a simple ON or OFF signal.

2. Analog and PWM

a.analogRead(pin): Unlike digital, this can measure values between 0 and 1023. This is useful for sensors like potentiometers or light sensors.
b.analogWrite(pin, value): This uses Pulse Width Modulation (PWM) to simulate analog voltages. It toggles the pin on and off very fast to dim an LED or control motor speed.
c.map(value, fromLow, fromHigh, toLow, toHigh): A mathematical shortcut. Since analogRead gives you up to 1023, but analogWrite only understands up to 255, map does the math to scale it down perfectly.

3. Communication and Timing

a.Serial.begin(baud): Required in setup if you want to see what's happening inside the code via the Serial Monitor.
b.Serial.println(data): Prints text or variables to your screen. This is the most important tool for "debugging" or fixing errors in your code.
c.delay(ms): Stops all code execution for the specified time. Use this sparingly, as the Arduino cannot listen for buttons while it is "sleeping" during a delay.
